(3484, 25, '2017-03-08 14:46:50', '2017-03-08 14:46:50', '<p>[{\"cellsNumber\":1,\"row\":\"Introduction\",\"lhsI\":\"Due%20to%20the%20%22mobile%22%20nature%20of%20the%20terminals%20and%20handsets%2C%20It%20is%20very%20common%20to%20observe%20a%20lot%20of%20Signalling%20resulted%20from%20changing%20the%20geographical%20location.%3Cbr%20/%3E%3Cbr%20/%3EMobile%20operators%20strive%20to%20assure%20service%20continuity%20during%20such%20procedures%20so%20whenever%20a%20user%20move%20between%20eNBs%2C%20MMEs%2C%20etc%2C%3B%20Service%20is%20not%20interrupted.%3Cbr%20/%3E%3Cbr%20/%3ETerms%20like%20Handover%20and%20Relocation%20always%20arise%20whenever%20there%20is%20a%20technical%20discussion%20describing%20these%20mobility%20procedures.%3Cbr%20/%3E%3Cbr%20/%3EThis%20comparison%20is%20assessing%20the%20Handover%20vs%20Relocation%20in%20LTE.\",\"rhsI\":\"\"},{\"cellsNumber\":2,\"row\":\"Definition\",\"lhsI\":\"Handover%20is%20a%20process%20executed%20by%20the%20eNB%20in%20which%20the%20UE%20is%20%22handovered%22%20to%20an%20adjacent%20Cell%20based%20on%20UE%20%28User%20Equipment%29%20RRC%20measurements.%3Cbr%20/%3E%3Cbr%20/%3EAn%20example%20of%20these%20measurements%20are%20the%20inter-frequency%20cells.%3Cbr%20/%3E%3Cbr%20/%3EControl%20Plane%26nbsp%3Band%20User%20Plane%20should%20be%20switched%20to%20the%20new%20Cell/Location%20without/with%20minimal%20Service%20interruption.\",\"rhsI\":\"Relocation%20is%20a%20process%20that%20is%20normally%20executed%20by%20the%20Network%20as%20a%20possible%20result%20of%20a%20Handover%20process%20in%20which%20a%20user%27s%20Control%20Plane%20and/or%20user%20plane%20is%20being%20relocated%20from%20one%20serving%20node%20to%20another%20serving%20node.%3Cbr%20/%3E%3Cbr%20/%3EFor%20example%2C%20an%20S1-Handover%20process%20may%20be%20corresponded%20by%20SGW%20Relocation.\"},{\"cellsNumber\":2,\"row\":\"Types\",\"lhsI\":\"Handovers%20can%20be%20classified%20into%26nbsp%3B%3Cbr%20/%3E%0A%3Cul%3E%0A%3Cli%3EHard%20Handover%20%28break-before-make%29%20where%20the%20resources%20are%20released%20first%20in%20the%20source%20cell%20before%20establishing%20the%20radio%20resources%20in%20the%20Destination%20Cell%20%28Data%20Handover%29%20where%20some%20packets%20maybe%20be%20buffered%20at%20Source%20eNB%20and%20to%20be%20transferred%20to%20Destination%20eNB%20once%20handover%20procedure%20is%20completed.%3C/li%3E%0A%3Cli%3ESoft%20Handover%20%28make-before-break%29%20where%20the%20UE%20can%20have%26nbsp%3Bthe%20resources%20in%20Destination%20Cell%20while%20holding%20resources%20in%20Source%20Cell%20to%20avoid%20call%20drops%20%28Voice%20Handover%29%3C/li%3E%0A%3C/ul%3E\",\"rhsI\":\"In%20LTE/EPC%2C%20It%20is%20very%20common%20to%20observe%20%3Cstrong%3ESGW%20Relocation%3C/strong%3E%20during%20Handovers%20such%20as%26nbsp%3BX2-based%20handover%20with%20%3Cstrong%3EServing%20GW%20relocation%3C/strong%3E.%3Cbr%20/%3E%3Cbr%20/%3ESame%20for%20%3Cstrong%3ERNC/eNB%3C/strong%3E%20during%20the%20IRAT%20Handover%20procedure.%20For%20example%2C%26nbsp%3BMME%20to%203G%20SGSN%20combined%20hard%20handover%20and%20%3Cstrong%3ESRNS%20relocation%3C/strong%3E%20procedure\"},{\"cellsNumber\":1,\"row\":\"Illustrative Example\",\"lhsI\":\"In%20this%20example%2C%20the%20UE%20is%20in%20%22active%22/Connected%20state.%3Cbr%20/%3EAlthough%20it%20is%20not%20common%2C%20But%20the%20two%20eNodeBs%20are%20integrated%20to%20the%20same%20MME%20and%20different%20SGWs.%3Cbr%20/%3ESource%20eNB%20decides%20that%20UE%20need%20to%20be%20handovered%20to%20the%20target%20eNB%20triggering%20the%20Handover%20procedure.%3Cbr%20/%3EIn%20this%20particular%20Case%2C%20Source%20eNB%20is%20covered%20by%20one%20SGW%20and%20the%20Target%20eNB%20is%20covered%20by%20another%20SGW%20therefore%20SGW%20relocation%20is%20mandatory.%3Cbr%20/%3EMME%20is%20the%20node%20that%20handles%20this%20kind%20of%20Coordination%20between%20the%20different%20Network%20Elements%20involved%20in%26nbsp%3B%3Cbr%20/%3E%3Cbr%20/%3E%3Cimg%20style%3D%22width%3A%20100%25%3B%20height%3A%20auto%3B%22%20src%3D%22../../wp-content/plugins/custom-qa/images/blobid1488992966905.png%22%20alt%3D%22%22%20/%3E\",\"rhsI\":\"\"}]</p>\n', 'Answer for What is the difference between Handover &amp; Relocation?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'answer-for-what-is-the-difference-between-handover-relocation', '', '', '2017-03-08 17:12:13', '2017-03-08 17:12:13', '', 3478, 'http://localhost/wp/dwqa-answer/answer-for-what-is-the-difference-between-handover-relocation/', 0, 'dwqa-answer', '', 0),
(3485, 55, '2017-03-08 15:38:18', '2017-03-08 15:38:18', '<p>[{\"cellsNumber\":2,\"row\":\"Definition\",\"lhsI\":\"Consecutive%20interpretation%20is%20one%20of%20the%20most%20common%20types%20of%20interpretation.The%20interpreter%20sits%20with%20the%20speaker%20in%20the%20same%20place%20be%20it%20a%20conference%20room%2C%20meeting%20or%20interview%20and%20takes%20notes%20of%20what%20is%20being%20said%20by%20the%20speaker.%20The%20speaker%20then%20pauses%20to%20let%20the%20interpreter%20render%20what%20he%20said.%20In%20other%20words%2C%20he%20translates%20segments%20not%20a%20run-on%20speech.\",\"rhsI\":\"This%20another%20common%20type%20where%20the%20interpreter%20sit%20in%20a%20sound-proof%20booth%20with%20a%20mic%20and%20a%20headset%20and%20render%20what%20the%20speaker%20is%20saying%20throughout%20his%20speech%3B%20listeners%20hear%20the%20translation%20via%20headphones.\"},{\"cellsNumber\":2,\"row\":\"Interaction with the Speaker\",\"lhsI\":\"There%20can%20be%20an%20interaction%20between%20the%20speaker%20and%20the%20interpreter.%26nbsp%3B\",\"rhsI\":\"There%20is%20usually%20little%20to%20no%20interaction%20between%20the%20speaker%20and%20the%20interpreter.\"}]</p>\n', 'Answer for What is the difference between Consecutive Interpretation &amp; Simultaneous Interpretation?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'answer-for-what-is-the-difference-between-consecutive-interpretation-simultaneous-interpretation', '', '', '2017-03-08 15:47:00', '2017-03-08 15:47:00', '', 3483, 'http://localhost/wp/dwqa-answer/answer-for-what-is-the-difference-between-consecutive-interpretation-simultaneous-interpretation/', 0, 'dwqa-answer', '', 0),
